               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1372" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1372" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1372" type="surname" value="OCKENDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1372" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD OCKENDEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, and live in Ely-place, South Lam<lb></lb>beth. On the 7th of Jan. I went with my grandchild to Oxford-market where I ought to receive my pension—on my way, near the Horse Guards, I met the prisoner—she followed us up to Oxford-market—I received a sove<lb></lb>reign, a half-sovereign, a half-crown, and three shillings—I gave that to my grand-daughter, for her grandmother—I then went to a public-house—the prisoner was with us, and I told her I had given my grand-daughter the money—we came out, and came on to Regent-street—I asked my little girl if she had got the money safe—she said, "Yes"—I said, "Let me look"—she took it out—it was in a piece of newspaper—I said, "Put it into your poc<lb></lb>ket, and take it home to your grandmother"—in coming along, I slipped down—I went into the Jolly Gardeners, and got the dirt off my coat—the prisoner was by me—when I was going home, in a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>, and told the child to pay, she said the prisoner had taken the money out of her pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1373" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1373" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1373" type="surname" value="OCKENDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1373" type="given" value="REBECCA HESTER"></interp>REBECCA HESTER OCKENDEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I shall be eleven years old next July. recollect having a sovereign, a half-sovereign, and some silver—I put it into my pocket, and when we got to the Jolly Gardeners my grandfather fell down—when we went into the house the prisoner sat beside me—I felt her putting her hand into my pocket, and when I felt afterwards the money was gone—no one but her could have taken it—I am sure she had it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1374" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1374" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1374" type="surname" value="COSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1374" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA COSTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I know the prisoner—she went away from me that morn<lb></lb>ing, and had no money at all—she came home in the evening, and she then had a half-sovereign and some silver.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I met the prosecutor; he asked me to go with him; when we got to the Jolly Gardeners I stopped some time, and then left him.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
